","about 1356":"omkring 1356","Keele, Staffordshire, England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Tunstall by Adbaston, Staffordshire, England":"Tunstall by Adbaston, Staffordshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1356–":"circa 1356–Overleden","1345–1402":"1345–1402","1356–Male":"1356–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1373–1384":"1373–1384","1378–1400":"1378–1400","1332–1390":"1332–1390","1322–Female":"1322–Overleden","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1356":"1356","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1332":"1332","about 1356":"circa 1356","Keele, Staffordshire, England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Tunstall by Adbaston, Staffordshire, England":"Tunstall by Adbaston, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"about 1356–":"about 1356–Deceased","1345–1402":"1345–1402","1356–Male":"1356–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1373–1384":"1373–1384","1378–1400":"1378–1400","1332–1390":"1332–1390","1322–Female":"1322–Deceased","1384":"1384","1373":"1373","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","1402":"1402","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","1356":"1356","1345":"1345","1322":"1322","1332":"1332","about 1356":"about 1356","Keele, Staffordshire, England":"Keele, Staffordshire, England","Tunstall by Adbaston, Staffordshire, England":"Tunstall by Adbaston, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tunstall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>tūn-stall</i> ‘site of a farm, farmstead’, notably Tunstall (Lancashire) and one or more of many Staffordshire places (Tunstall near Stoke on Trent, Tunstall near Adbaston, and four places called Dunstall), but also Tunstall Farm in Mountfield (Sussex) and possibly also Tunstall (Durham, Kent, Norfolk, Shropshire, Suffolk, east and North Yorkshire), and Dunstall (Lincolnshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tunstill","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Tunstall  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sneyd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Sneyd in Burslem (Staffordshire), The Sneyd near Bloxwich (also Staffordshire), or Snead Farm and Snead Common in Rock (Worcestershire), all of which derived from Middle English <i>snede</i>, Old English <i>snǣd</i> ‘detached piece of land or woodland’. Compare   Snaith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Snaith","meanings":["English: habitational name from Snaith in Yorkshire. The placename derives from Old Norse <i>sneith</i> ‘slice of land, piece of land cut off’."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":26,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.o